0.1 Introduction

In this session, we will perform a series of analyses that can be performed on already-clustered single-cell data, including:

  • Assignment of cell labels using a reference dataset.
  • Identification of marker genes for clusters for de novo cell label assignment.
  • Differential expression analysis.
  • Differential abundance analysis.

This tutorial is based on the following resources:

  • Azimuth tutorial
  • “Orchestrating single-cell analysis with Bioconductor” book chapters:
    • Marker gene detection
    • Cell type annotation
  • Seurat Differential Expression testing vignette
  • Milo demo vignette

0.4 Assignment of cell labels using a reference dataset.

After clustering cells, it might be difficult (or even risky) to assign cell identities blindly. When well-curated references are available, cells can be confidently and rapidly annotated by mapping to already-characterized cell atlases.

The Azimuth R package provides not only functions, but also integrated references for multiple human tissues, including bone marrow. These are installed via the SeuratData package, which contains the following references:

available_data <- AvailableData()

0.5 Assignment of cell labels de novo using marker genes

Strategies for cell labelling are often based on the definition of marker genes, i.e. genes that are highly expressed in each cell type. This is useful when only the identities of the markers are available.

First, to find the genes that are significantly highly expressed in each cell type, we will use the scoreMarkers() function from the scran R package. This function compares each pair of clusters and computes scores quantifying the differences in the expression distributions between clusters.

Importantly, scran belongs to the family of R packages that are based on the SingleCellExperiment data class, so we will need to transform our SeuratObject and correctly fill the slots with the normalized and log-transformed counts:

setty_sce <- as.SingleCellExperiment(setty_seurat)
colLabels(setty_sce) <- setty_sce$ident
normcounts(setty_sce) <- setty_seurat[["RNA"]]@data
logcounts(setty_sce) <- log2(normcounts(setty_sce)+1)

table(setty_sce$predicted.celltype.l2)
## 
##         BaEoMa      CD14 Mono      CD4 Naive            CLP    Early Eryth 
##             87              8             26            301            398 
##            EMP            GMP            HSC     Late Eryth           LMPP 
##            182            477            432             39            500 
##       Memory B            pDC          pre B        pre-mDC        pre-pDC 
##              1             27            337              2             49 
##          pro B        Prog Mk transitional B 
##             73             38              6

Now, we will apply the scoreMarkers() function. We will define a minimum log fold-change of 1 to consider a gene as relevant to prevent small changes to drive the detected markers:

markers <- scoreMarkers(setty_sce, 
                        groups = colLabels(setty_sce),
                        lfc = 1)

colnames(markers[[1]])
##  [1] "self.average"          "other.average"         "self.detected"        
##  [4] "other.detected"        "mean.logFC.cohen"      "min.logFC.cohen"      
##  [7] "median.logFC.cohen"    "max.logFC.cohen"       "rank.logFC.cohen"     
## [10] "mean.AUC"              "min.AUC"               "median.AUC"           
## [13] "max.AUC"               "rank.AUC"              "mean.logFC.detected"  
## [16] "min.logFC.detected"    "median.logFC.detected" "max.logFC.detected"   
## [19] "rank.logFC.detected"

The markers list contains one table per cluster including the marker scores for each gene in that cluster. Since this is a very long list, and not all genes will be relevant, we need to select one of these variables to rank markers and subset the list.

A good metric to do this is Area Under the Curve (AUC), which measures our ability to distinguish between two distributions in a pairwise comparison. The AUC represents the probability that a randomly chosen observation from our cluster of interest is greater than a randomly chosen observation from the other cluster. A value of 1 corresponds to upregulation, where all values of our cluster of interest are greater than any value from the other cluster; a value of 0.5 means that there is no net difference in the location of the distributions; and a value of 0 corresponds to downregulation.

Let’s focus on cluster 2, and select the top 100 genes with the largest mean AUC:

selected_cluster <- "2"

markers_select <- markers[[selected_cluster]]

top_markers <- order(markers_select$mean.AUC, 
                     decreasing = TRUE)[1:100]

markers_select[top_markers,1:4]

Let’s plot the top markers in the cluster using the plotExpression() function in the scater QC R package:

plotExpression(setty_sce, 
               features = c("XACT", "ZNF385D", "CRACD", 
                            "ST8SIA6", "PDZD8"),
               x = "label", colour_by = "label")

While this is very interesting, gene names may not mean anything by themselves. To better interpret the list of markers for cluster 2, we will test these genes for enrichment of gene sets in the Gene Ontology (GO). Doing this, we will get a sense of the biological processes that are active in each cell type, which can give us clues regarding cell type identities.

There are many ways to do this, but in this case, we will use the limma R package and the goana() function, which performs a hypergeometric test to identify GO terms that are overrepresented in our marker subset.

Since some of our gene IDs are in ENSEMBL format and others are gene symbols, and this function requires them to be Entrez IDs, we will map the identifiers to obtain the Entrez equivalents using the genome-wide human annotation:

library(org.Hs.eg.db)
## Loading required package: AnnotationDbi
## 
# map gene IDs to database
entrez_ids_ens <- mapIds(org.Hs.eg.db, 
                     keys = rownames(markers_select), 
                     column = "ENTREZID", keytype = "ENSEMBL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
entrez_ids_symb <- mapIds(org.Hs.eg.db, 
                     keys = rownames(markers_select), 
                     column = "ENTREZID", keytype = "SYMBOL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
# merge
entrez_ids_symb[is.na(entrez_ids_symb)] <- entrez_ids_ens[is.na(entrez_ids_symb)]

Now, we can run the goana() enrichment analysis on our top markers vs all markers:

library(limma)

go_out <- goana(entrez_ids_symb[top_markers], 
                species = "Hs", 
                universe = entrez_ids_symb)

# Only keeping biological process terms that are not overly general
go_out <- go_out[order(go_out$P.DE),]
go_useful <- go_out[go_out$Ont=="BP" & go_out$N <= 150,]
head(go_useful[,c(1,3,4)], 40)

If we check the GO database for the most enriched term, “definitive hemopoiesis”, we find that this corresponds to an intermediate state in erythrocyte differentiation. While other terms point to earlier stages in blood cell differentiation, such as “embryonic hemopoiesis” and “negative regulation of myeloid cell differentiation”, terms such as “heme metabolic process” and “tetrapyrrole catabolic process” and “intracellular iron ion homeostasis” point to hemoglobin metabolism, suggesting that these cells are erythrocytes or late-stage erythrocyte precursors. If you go back to the Azimuth cell type annotation results, you see that this cluster is in fact labelled as early erythrocytes.

0.6 Differential Expression analysis

Even though marker gene detection is based on approaches that are similar to those for Differential Expression (DE) analysis, we may want to obtain more detailed results regarding the DE genes between two specific clusters. To achieve this, we will use the SeuratObject and the Azimuth cell type identity results.

The bulk of Seurat’s differential expression features can be accessed through the FindMarkers() function. To test for differential expression between two specific groups of cells, we will specify the ident.1 and ident.2 parameters. Let’s perform a DE analysis comparing Common Lymphoid Progenitor (CLP) cells to a more differentiated stage, pre-B cells:

table(setty_seurat$predicted.celltype.l2)
## 
##         BaEoMa      CD14 Mono      CD4 Naive            CLP    Early Eryth 
##             87              8             26            301            398 
##            EMP            GMP            HSC     Late Eryth           LMPP 
##            182            477            432             39            500 
##       Memory B            pDC          pre B        pre-mDC        pre-pDC 
##              1             27            337              2             49 
##          pro B        Prog Mk transitional B 
##             73             38              6
preB_markers <- FindMarkers(setty_seurat, 
                                     group.by = "predicted.celltype.l2",
                                     ident.1 = "pre B", 
                                     ident.2 = "CLP",
                                     logfc.threshold = 1)

head(preB_markers, 10)
##                   p_val avg_log2FC pct.1 pct.2     p_val_adj
## EBF1      9.311137e-109   3.272240 0.991 0.076 2.349014e-104
## AKAP12    8.518211e-100   2.319360 0.923 0.037  2.148974e-95
## VPREB3     1.191424e-98   2.416789 0.920 0.037  3.005725e-94
## SPINK2     4.262403e-97  -2.414343 0.148 0.930  1.075319e-92
## VPREB1     1.023068e-96   2.316650 0.982 0.233  2.580997e-92
## ATP8B4     1.880834e-90  -2.261311 0.050 0.847  4.744969e-86
## DNTT       2.530229e-81   1.872062 1.000 0.704  6.383262e-77
## LINC02580  3.292738e-80   2.123462 0.861 0.096  8.306919e-76
## CD44       1.488296e-76  -1.810185 0.154 0.867  3.754673e-72
## BACH2      3.119194e-76   2.235109 0.941 0.462  7.869103e-72

See how T cell development markers CD44 is significantly more highly expressed in CLP cells in comparison to pre-B cells.

The results data frame has the following columns :

  • p_val : unadjusted p-value.
  • avg_log2FC : log fold-change of the average expression between the two groups. Positive values indicate that the feature is more highly expressed in the first group.
  • pct.1 : The percentage of cells where the feature is detected in the first group.
  • pct.2 : The percentage of cells where the feature is detected in the second group.
  • p_val_adj : Adjusted p-value, based on Bonferroni correction using all features in the dataset.

NOTE: this function can also be used to define marker genes, as we did in the previous section, however, it is based on a different approach: instead of performing all pairwise comparisons, it compares cells from the selected cell type to all the remaining cells. To do this, simply set ident.1 and leave ident.2 = NULL.

NOTE 2: by default, this function uses a Wilcoxon rank sum test, although other methods are supported (see ?FindMarkers() and the Seurat DE vignette referenced above for help).

0.7 Differential Abundance analysis

Differential Abundance (DA) analysis is designed to detect changes in cell and cell type composition across conditions in single-cell datasets. To demonstrate how to perform DA analysis, we will use the miloR package. While differential abundance (DA) is commonly quantified in discrete cell clusters, Milo uses a network of cell-to-cell similarities builg using the k-Nearest Neighbours (KNN) method, and then analyzes partially overlapping neighbourhoods of cells on the KNN graph to test for DA.

For this, we will load a pre-processed version of the Setty et al. dataset in which single-cell data from two different individuals, have been integrated. We will therefore test DA between both donors.

NOTE: we have added replicate information to the “replicate” column in the metadata table, generating a replicated multi-condition experiment, which is the requirement for Milo. Usually, experiments will contain technical replicate or batch information associated with sequencing. In this case, however, replicate tags were randomly added to cells from each individual to allow for miloR to be run.

setty_combined <- LoadH5Seurat("../HandsOn4_CellType_Analysis/data_preparation/setty_combined_rep1-rep2.h5seurat",
                               verbose = FALSE)
## Validating h5Seurat file
## Warning: Adding a command log without an assay associated with it
setty_combined
## An object of class Seurat 
## 53987 features across 4983 samples within 5 assays 
## Active assay: refAssay (25969 features, 2840 variable features)
##  4 other assays present: RNA, integrated, prediction.score.celltype.l1, prediction.score.celltype.l2
##  4 dimensional reductions calculated: ref.umap, pca, tsne, integrated_dr
DimPlot(setty_combined, reduction = "tsne",
        group.by = "predicted.celltype.l2")

DimPlot(setty_combined, reduction = "pca",
        group.by = "individual")

Observe how PCA does not separate cells by individual, which is an indicator of successful integration.

First, we need to transform this to a SingleCellExperiment object, which will then be converted to a Milo object, a related class used by the miloR package:

# build SingleCellExperiment object
combined_sce <- as.SingleCellExperiment(setty_combined, 
                                        assay = "integrated")
combined_sce <- runPCA(combined_sce)

# build Milo object
combined_milo <- Milo(combined_sce)

# remove SingleCellExperiment object to free memory
rm(setty_combined)

Next, we need to add the KNN graph to the Milo object. This is stored in the graph slot in the Milo object. The miloR package includes functionality to build and store the graph from the PCA dimensions stored in the reducedDim slot.

We will define two parameters: - k: the number of cell nearest-neighbours to use for KNN graph building - d: the number of reduced dimensions to use for KNN graph building

combined_milo <- buildGraph(combined_milo, k = 50, d = 50)
## Constructing kNN graph with k:50

Now, we will define the neighbourhood of each cell, i.e. the index, which is dfined as the group of cells connected by an edge in the KNN graph to the index cell. We will set k and d to the same values as before, and prop=0.2, which corresponds to the proportion of cells to randomly sample to start the algorithm.

combined_milo <- makeNhoods(combined_milo, prop = 0.2,
                            k = 50, d = 50, refined = FALSE)
## Checking valid object

Once we have defined neighbourhoods, it’s good to take a look at how big the neighbourhoods are (i.e. how many cells form each neighbourhood). This affects the power of DA testing. We can check this out using the plotNhoodSizeHist function. Empirically, we found it’s best to have a distribution peaking between 50 and 100. Otherwise you might consider rerunning makeNhoods increasing k and/or prop:

plotNhoodSizeHist(combined_milo)

NOTE: for this tutorial, the k and d parameters have been adjusted to generate a distribution that satisifed this indicator. In a real-life scenario, we would need to adjust the parameters again to generate an adequate size of neighbourhoods for our data.

Now we have to count how many cells from each sample are in each neighbourhood. We need to use the cell metadata, contained in the SingleCellExperiment object, and specify which column contains the replicate (i.e. sample) information:

combined_milo <- countCells(combined_milo,
                            meta.data = data.frame(colData(combined_sce)),
                            samples = "replicate")
## Checking meta.data validity
## Counting cells in neighbourhoods

This adds to the Milo object a n \times m matrix, where n is the number of neighbourhoods and m is the number of experimental samples (in our case, the replicates). Values indicate the number of cells from each sample counted in a neighbourhood. This count matrix will be used for DA testing.

head(nhoodCounts(combined_milo))
## 6 x 4 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
##   I1_rep1 I1_rep2 I2_rep1 I2_rep2
## 1      17      35      19      12
## 2       7      13      25      21
## 3       8      11      16      20
## 4      25      43      27      31
## 5      20      20      19      16
## 6       7      25      20      31

Now we are all set to test for differential abundance in neighbourhoods. miloR implement this hypothesis testing in a generalized linear model (GLM) framework, specifically using the Negative Binomial GLM implementation in edgeR.

We first need to think about our experimental design. The design matrix should match the replicates to a condition of interest, in this case, the donors defined in the individual column. As a result, we will compare DA across the two donors:

design <- data.frame(replicate = colnames(nhoodCounts(combined_milo)),
                     individual = c("Ind1", "Ind1", "Ind2", "Ind2"))
rownames(design) <- design$replicate

design
##         replicate individual

Milo uses a type of False Discovery Rate (FDR) correction that accounts for the overlap between neighbourhoods, i.e. cells may belong to different neighbourhoods and therefore be tested multiple times during DA analysis. To use this correction, we first need to store the distances between nearest neighbors in the Milo object using the calcNhoodDistance() function:

combined_milo <- calcNhoodDistance(combined_milo, d = 50)
## 'as(<dgTMatrix>, "dgCMatrix")' is deprecated.
## Use 'as(., "CsparseMatrix")' instead.
## See help("Deprecated") and help("Matrix-deprecated").

Since this can be memory intensive, we have stored a versino of the Milo object with pre-computed distances that you can load:

combined_milo <- readRDS("../HandsOn4_CellType_Analysis/processed_data/combined_milo_NhoodDist.rds")

Then, we will do the test using the testNhoods() function and our experimental design matrix. This calculates a Fold-change and corrected P-value for each neighbourhood, which will indicate whether there is significant differential abundance between indidivuals.

da_results <- testNhoods(combined_milo, 
                         design = ~ individual, 
                         design.df = design)
## Using TMM normalisation
## Performing spatial FDR correction withk-distance weighting

Finally, to visualize the DA results, we build an abstracted graph of neighbourhoods that we can plot together with the single-cell reduced dimension plot:

combined_milo <- buildNhoodGraph(combined_milo)

combined_milo <- runUMAP(combined_milo)

# load palettes for visualization
library(paletteer)

plotUMAP(combined_milo, colour_by = "predicted.celltype.l2", point_size = 0.5) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = paletteer_d("ggsci::default_ucscgb"))
## Scale for colour is already present.
## Adding another scale for colour, which will replace the existing scale.

plotNhoodGraphDA(combined_milo, da_results, alpha = 0.05)

Comparing these plots side by side, we observe that there are particularly large abundance changes in the area where pre-B cells accumulate, indicating that there are less B cells in individual 2 compared to individual 1. Similar patterns are observed in yellow-colored cells, which in this case correspond to Lympho-Myeloid Pirmed Progenitor (LMPP) cells. All in all, we may hypothesize that individual 1 has a larger amount of progenitors that differentiate into B/T lymphocytes than individual 2.
